issue.body:
I've read through the docs on directives, scopes, and transcluding. I think I have a pretty good understanding of what's going on. I understand why a directive that uses transclude automatically gets a new scope; but I would like the option to disable the behavior.

For components, it is true that you probably want a new scope. However, for containers, you probably don't want a new scope. A container is an element that does not explicitly know about it children and subsequently there is no way to wire up values and functions using the '=', '&', '@' values in the scope.

It would be great if I could specify, to NOT create a new scope.

comment.body:
The use case is that I want the children of a component that uses transclusion to still bind to a higher level scope. For instance, if I have a page level controller declared on the body tag. Then in the body there several nested components, some of which use transclusion, and eventually there is a form. I want the inputs on that form to bind to values on the page controller. As far as I can tell, this is not immediately or easily possible. This is well documented and there are several documented work arounds. 

https://github.com/angular/angular.js/wiki/The-Nuances-of-Scope-Prototypal-Inheritance
http://docs.angularjs.org/guide/directive

This is a primary use case so I don't want a work around. And even with the work arounds, they don't solve for dynamic cases in which a component that uses transclusion has a dynamic set of children.

The Angular project is very well done; so far the best JS framework I have seen. Unfortunately, I have decided not to pursue it anymore, I feel that the scoping/binding architecture is too complicated and misses the mark. Ultimately I'm looking for a framework that supports an elegant solution for two way binding and a component library; which I think Angular falls short.

Good luck, I look forward to seeing the project progress!

pull_request.body:
When using AngularJS with a server-side framework that requires a URL suffix like .json then angular will keep the suffix for all resource variants. So when you have a POST or index request then you end up having URLs that look like "/resource/.json".

Here's the issue in detail:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/11622665/format-all-model-service-urls-to-include-json-in-angular-js

I've added the code into the repo to fix this. By setting a _suffix variable in the params{} hash when creating a resource then the suffix can be added properly.

commits.message: docs(guide): change example controller to properly call greet method on greeter

pull_request.body:
doc(guide): In DI, add missing greet method to greeter service in $scope.sayHello

MyController defines a $scope.sayHello function to demo the greeter service. But the actual greet method was omitted in the example code. Now instead of greeter('Hello World') we call greeter.greet('Hello World') to match the object returned from the greeter factory.
